<h3 align="center"> Information on Coronavirus or COVID-19</h3>
<br><p><b><u>Update: 2:00 PM, Thursday, March 12</u></b></p>
							<p>The Bonner School administration continues to monitor on a daily basis developments related to COVID-19.  As of this writing, there are <u>no COVID-19 cases</u> in our school or in the Missoula area.  We remain in close contact with Missoula City-County Health Department and other community leaders and decision-makers.  We are discussing a range of considerations in how Bonner School serves students in the weeks ahead.  The Centers for Disease Control is not recommending school closures as a response, and Bonner School would most likely only close schools at the direction or recommendation of the State of Montana or Missoula City-County Health Department.</p>
							<p>If Bonner School were to change our current operations, we will be in immediate contact with parents/guardians via text message and/or robo-call.  We are committed to protecting the health and safety of Bonner students and their families.</p>
							<p>If you have questions or concerns, please feel free to speak with Superintendent Jim Howard, Principal Shelley Andres, or School Nurse, Lindsay Larson, at 258-6151.</p>
<br><hr>
<p>There are no cases of COVID-19 at Bonner School,  but our leadership team has been in close communication with Missoula City County Health Department (MCCHD) and other safety and health agencies to monitor the Coronavirus (COVID-19) situation in our school and broader community.  While there are no confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Montana, if or when cases occur in our community we will keep parents/guardians informed by text and/or the school website and follow that with frequent updates as necessary.</p>
							<p>For the most up-to-date  and accurate local information about the Coronavirus, please visit <a href="https://www.missoulacounty.us/government/health/health-department/emergency-preparedness/coronavirus" target="_blank">Missoula Public Health Department’s website</a>.</p>
							<p>Meantime, Bonner School will follow US Centers for Disease Control (CDC), Montana Department of Public Health and Human Services (Montana DPHHS), and the Missoula City County Health Department (MCCHD) recommendations to prevent any infection of any respiratory virus, including:</p>
							<p></p>
<ul>
<li>Staff and students should stay home when they are ill with symptoms that prevent them from participating in their normal school activities</li>
								<li>Wash hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.</li>
								<li>Avoid touching eyes, nose and mouth with unwashed hands.</li>
								<li>Avoid close contact with people who are sick.</li>
								<li>Cough or sneeze into an elbow or use a tissue and place immediately in the trash.</li>
								<li>Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces using a regular household cleaning spray or wipe.</li>
								<li>Encourage your child to bring a personal water bottle to school and use the water bottle filling station instead of drinking directly from the water fountain.</li>
							</ul>
<p>Here are some additional precautions we are taking here at Bonner School to protect staff and student safety:</p>
							<p></p>
<ul>
<li>Our school nurse, Lindsay Larson is in regular communication with County health professionals and closely monitoring any staff or students who may be exhibiting any respiratory symptoms.</li>
								<li>We are temporarily staffing up our custodial team, led by Bill Wilsonoff, to increase the frequency and scope of our existing high-touch disinfecting protocols</li>
								<li>Classroom teachers, assisted by nurse Lindsay Larson, are providing expanded teach-to opportunities for students to frequently and thoroughly wash their hands.</li>
							</ul>
<p>If COVID-19 cases were to impact our area, Bonner School will follow guidance from Missoula City-County Health Department to determine when to exclude any students from school and and will collaborate with them on considerations for closing schools due to high numbers of ill staff and students or for deep cleaning.</p>
							<p>To help prevent the spread of misinformation about the Coronavirus, please avail yourself of a wealth of accurate information available on the <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/index.html" target="_blank">Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) website</a>, the <a href="https://dphhs.mt.gov/publichealth/cdepi/diseases/coronavirusmt" target="_blank">Montana Department of Health and Human Services website</a> and the <a href="https://www.missoulacounty.us/government/health/health-department/emergency-preparedness/coronavirus" target="_blank">Missoula City-County Health Department website</a>.</p>
							<p>Another helpful immediate resource is Missoula City-County Health Department’s <b>Call Center</b>:  You can speak to a real person who will provide current information at <b>258-INFO</b> or <b>258-4636</b>.</p>
							<p>Here are some additional helpful sites:</p>
							<p></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/about/share-facts.html" target="_blank">Facts About COVID-19</a></li>
								<li><a href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-nCoV/index.html" target="_blank">CDC COVID-19 home page</a></li>
								<li>Video explaining <a href="https://youtu.be/drMw2evwMFA" target="_blank">Novel Coronavirus</a>
</li>
								<li><a href="https://youtu.be/qJG72sycQB8" target="_blank">Kid-friendly Handwashing video</a></li>
							</ul>
<p>Thank you for your help in keeping our students and staff safe and healthy.</p>
							<p>Jim Howard<br>Superintendent</p>
